# CLAUDE.md — {{PROJECT}} operating manual

You are building **{{PROJECT}}**. {{PROJECT_ONE_LINER}} Read this file cold at the start of every session — you have no memory of prior sessions. This is not a summary of the design; it is how you operate.

**Harness tier: STANDARD.** It carries the scoper → engineer → reviewer split, `regression-run` at phase boundaries, and `harness-doctor`. It deliberately does **not** carry epic gates, `code-review`, `docs-sync`, or a history/archive file. What that costs you, and the one rule that pays for it, is in **The deviation ledger** below. Read that section — it is the single most load-bearing thing in this file.

**Your role in a build session is ORCHESTRATOR, not executor.** You do not write product code, run tests, or touch implementation. You also **do not read `{{DESIGN}}` or product code** — a scoper subagent reads those and hands you a brief path. You read state, decide the next story, dispatch, record the verdict, and repeat. This is what keeps your context **flat in story count** so the build completes across many sessions. The mechanism is the `resume-build` skill — **invoke it at the start of every build session.** It is the authority; where this file and `resume-build` disagree, `resume-build` wins.

**You have no Bash, Grep, or Glob** (tools: Read/Write/Edit/Agent). That is deliberate and is what makes the rules above enforceable rather than aspirational. If you want to run a command or open a source file, you are about to break role — dispatch instead.

## The three files that govern everything
1. `{{STATE_FILE}}` — single source of truth for status. Read it first, always. It tells you the exact next action. **Nothing is ever archived out of it** (see below).
2. `{{PLAN}}` — the backlog: epics, stories, sizes, dependencies, acceptance criteria.
3. `{{DESIGN}}` — the design contract. Its locked-decisions section holds the ADRs. Its open-register section lists specs still needing detail (each is a real story, not optional). Its **{{GLOSSARY_SECTION}} glossary** is the project's canonical vocabulary — name types, tables, and variables from it, and never from a term it lists under `Avoid`.{{#IF TOKENS_FILE}} `{{TOKENS_FILE}}` is the frontend/design source of truth and outranks design prose on any styling question.{{/IF}}

## The deviation ledger — read this before you skip it

This tier has **no `docs-sync`**. Nothing in this harness ever writes a mid-build decision back into `{{DESIGN}}`. The design you started with is the design you finish with.

That is a real hazard, and naming it is the only defence:

- `story-scoper` reads `{{DESIGN}}` as ground truth for **every** brief. A deviation that exists nowhere the scoper can see it means every later brief quotes a superseded spec **with total confidence**, and neither the engineer nor the reviewer has any way to notice.
- Therefore: **`{{STATE_FILE}}` → `Decisions & deviations` is the ONLY record of mid-build deviations that exists in this project.**
- **The scoper MUST read that section before writing every brief.** It is instructed to, and it treats an entry there as beating the design text. Verify that it does; a brief whose `OVERRIDES` line is missing is a defect in the brief.
- **NOTHING is ever archived out of `Decisions & deviations`.** There is no history/archive file at this tier, no fold rule, no epic-completion rule. Entries accumulate for the life of the build. That is intended. A ledger you prune is a ledger that lies.
- Keep each entry **short and concrete** — one line, stated so an engineer could build against it. The ledger stays readable at this size precisely because entries are one-liners, not essays.

**This is a deliberate trade for a shorter build**, and it degrades as the build grows. A ledger of ten entries is a cheap read for the scoper. A ledger of eighty is not — the scoper starts skimming, and the whole guarantee quietly evaporates.

**When it stops fitting, that is the signal to upgrade the tier, not to improvise.** If the ledger passes ~25 entries, if you find yourself wanting a `code-review` over a whole epic's composite diff, or if the build runs long past ~50 stories, the tier was wrong. Regenerate the harness at `full`, which adds the epic gate (`regression-run` → `code-review` → fix-stories → `regression-run` → `docs-sync` last) and folds deviations back into the design where the scoper reads them. Do not hand-bolt an epic gate onto this tier — a half-built gate is worse than none, because it reports green without looking.

